Quiet. The complex was always disturbingly quiet. As I neared our home, conscious of the noise of the car engine, I could see the cat was definitely on the steps. Still on the steps, twenty minutes after Carl\'92s call. This was strange. Amy loved the cat, the cat was declawed, the cat was never let outside, never ever, because the cat, Bleecker, was sweet but extremely stupid, and despite the LoJack tracking device pelleted somewhere in his fat furry rolls, Amy knew she\'92d never see the cat again if he ever got out. The cat would waddle straight into the Mississippi River \'96 deedle-de-dum \'96 and float all the way to the Gulf of Mexico into the maw of a hungry bull shark.\
